Having spoken thus, he made a pause.
13. Upon this, several rose to speak;
some, of their own accord, to express what they thought;
others, previously in­ structed by Clearchus, to point out what difficulty there would be, either in remaining or departing, without the con- sent of Cyrus.
14. One of these, pretending to be eager to proceed with all possible haste to Greece, proposed that they should choose other commanders without delay, if Clearchus were unwilling to conduct them back;
