44. Many other persons, too, sent notice to Xenophon that be had been made an object of calumny, and ought to be upon his guard.
Xenophon, on receiving these communications, took two victims and sacri­ ficed to Jupiter, consulting him whether it would be better for him to stay with Seuthes on the conditions that he pro­ posed, or to go away with the army.
Jupiter signified to him that he had better depart.
