I. Antipho ridicules the poverty and frugality of Socrates, and his forbearance to receive pay for his in­ structions, sect.
1—3;
Socrates replies that, by not receiving remunera­ tion, he is more at liberty to choose his audience, 4, 5 ;
that there are various advantages attendant on plainness of diet and dress, 6, 7;
