Finding that one of his followers was neglectful of a friend who was oppressed with poverty, he asked Antisthenes, in the presence of the man that neglected his friend, and of several others, saying, “Are there certain settled values for friends, Antis­ thenes, as there are for slaves?
2. For, of slaves, one, per­ haps, is worth two minæ, another not even half a mina, ano­ ther five minæ, another ten.
Nicias, the SOil of Niceratus, is said to have bought an overseer for his silver mines1 at the prise of a whole talent.
